# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
classic lower bound and upper bound problem 

equation can be written as
$$lower-nums[i]<=nums[j]<=upper-nums[i]$$
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->


1) sort the array , the condition `0 <= i < j < n` is redundant.(observe carefully)
2) now if i am at `nums[i]`
to find how many elements that we can add to nums[i] such that they are in range $$[lower-nums[i],upper-nums[i]]$$
->since the array is sorted and we have to find these numbers from index (i+1,n) we can find the range of the number for particualr element `nums[i]`.
-> to find the **low index** range simply use upper_bound `(low)`
-> to find the **high index** range simply use upper_bound `(high)`
3) add  `high-low` in your answer

# Complexity
- Time complexity: `O(nlogn)`
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:`O(1)`
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long countFairPairs(vector<int>& nums, int lower, int upper) 
    {
        sort(begin(nums),end(nums));
        long long ans = 0,n = nums.size();
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++)
        {
            int low=lower_bound(begin(nums) + i + 1,end(nums),lower - nums[i]) - begin(nums);
            int high=upper_bound(begin(nums) + i + 1,end(nums),upper - nums[i]) - begin(nums);
            ans += 1LL*(high - low);
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

