# Intuition
Initially I thought of using a multiset but subtracting iterators is very costly in non linear data structures like set, multiset.
The next thing which struck my mind was whether I can sort the array or not and as it turns out, I can.

# Approach>
First, sort the array. It can be seen that it won't change the answer as the indices of elements are not important at all.

For every element, we just need to find the number of elements which are in a specific range.(Just write down the equations on paper and it's easy to see the constraints on the lowerbound and upperbound).

Lower bound function gives the first number which is in this "specific" range and upper bound gives the first number which is not.

Subtract them and one more question solved successfully.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(nlogn)    thanks to sorting and lower_bound upper_bound functions

- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    typedef long long ll;
    long long countFairPairs(vector<int>& a, int lower, int upper) {
        ll ans = 0;
        sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        int n = a.size();

        for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
            auto it1 = lower_bound(a.begin(), a.begin()+i, lower - a[i]);
            auto it2 = upper_bound(a.begin(), a.begin()+i, upper - a[i]);
            if(it2 > it1)   ans += (it2 - it1);
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
```

