# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
If we don't sort the array, it will end up in TLE with brute force solution.
For i-th element in nums, we can find a fair window `(left, right]` where from `(i, left+1)` to `(i, right)` are fair pairs.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The key point is to find the `left` boundary and the `right` boundary.
`left`: the smallest index that doesn't satisfy nums[i] + nums[left] >= lower.
`right`: the largest index that satisfy nums[i] + nums[right] <= upper.
Therefore, we can say there are (right - (left+1) + 1) = (right - left) pairs for i-th element.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(n^2)$$
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
$$O(1)$$

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public long CountFairPairs(int[] nums, int lower, int upper) {
        long count = 0;
        Array.Sort(nums);
        int left=nums.Length - 1, right=nums.Length - 1;
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.Length-1; i++) {
            left = Math.Max(left, i+1);
            while(left > i && nums[i] + nums[left] >= lower){
                left--;
            }
            while(right>i && nums[i] + nums[right] > upper){
                right--;
            }
            if (right < left)
                break;
            count += right-left;
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

