# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Using a given `nums[j]`, consider intergers `nums[i]` satisfying `lower <= nums[i] + nums[j] <= upper`.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Sort an array with respect to intergers. Here let us consider the index `j` and then we could consider the range where an index `i` satisfies the condition `lower <= nums[i] + nums[j] <= upper`.

First, the minimum index (iterator) satifying `lower <= nums[i] + nums[j]` is written as `auto left = lower_bound(nums.begin(), &nums[i], lower - nums[j])` and the maximum index satifying `nums[i] + nums[j] <= upper` is written as `upper_bound(nums.begin(), iter, upper - v)--`. Then the number of indecies satisfying the condition is given as the difference of these two indecies. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(nlogn), where n is the size of a given array.
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n).
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long countFairPairs(vector<int>& nums, int lower, int upper) {
        sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());
        long long int ans = 0;
        auto iter = nums.begin();
        iter++;
        while(iter != nums.end()){
            int v = *iter;
            auto left = lower_bound(nums.begin(), iter, lower - v);
            auto right = upper_bound(nums.begin(), iter, upper - v);
            right--;
            ans += (right - left) + 1;
            iter++;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

